ty of inquiry in online learning environmentsthe risks and rewards of co-teachingreaching and teaching ";non-traditional"; studentsfacilitating learning and leadership in student team projectsconnecting students with the community through researchissues of assessment, including backward design, developing and using rubrics, and defining and implementing the scholarship of teaching and learning Through Learning from Each Other, all faculty who care about their teaching, but especially faculty in the social sciences, can successfully employ curricular innovations, classroom techniques, and advances in assessment to create better learning environments for their students.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aChin, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aKozimor-King, Michele Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520969032.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles